			<h3 ><a href="#p173234">Re: Please, I'm becoming crazy to correct to translate this.</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="http://thejapanesepage.com/forum/viewtopic.php?p=173234&amp;sid=2e8aa4ddff51be967e1ce83a84046378#p173234"><img src="http://thejapanesepage.com/phpbb/styles/tjp-embed/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="http://thejapanesepage.com/forum/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=6030&amp;sid=2e8aa4ddff51be967e1ce83a84046378" style="color: #00AA00;" class="username-coloured">Ongakuka</a></strong> &raquo; Thu 03.22.2012 8:04 am </p>

			

			<div class="content"><blockquote class="uncited"><div>ããããã is not passive. It's used with ãã to express an unintentional action.</div></blockquote><br /><br />The second part I can agree with, but there is no denying that ããããã is the passive voice. To say otherwise is very misleading! Anyway, when we translate this sentence we don't need to keep the verb in the passive voice if the English can be expressed more naturally without it.<br /><br />For example, something like '...I begin to wonder if there could be some other forms of expression/ways to express myself'<br /><br />As you know, the art of translation is keeping the balance of accuracy, faithfulness to the original, and keeping the translation sounding natural in the target language.</div>

